segments.text: Please return this copy to Army Services Technical Information Center, Dayton, Ohio.
So presumably this is where a lot of the Air Force documents.
They were in Dayton, Ohio, the not-building Dayton, Ohio.
Were accumulated at one time or another, but then this goes back where they are now.
It's hard to say.
Okay.
Now, the next few questions I wanted to ask you to close off the technical oil mission part.
I have to do with questions other people should like for an answer on, if it's possible.
If you were going to begin to catalog the documents, that is to abstract them and to index them and place them on a computer, would you begin with the technical oil mission documents first?
Well, are you considering all the technology in synthetic fuels or just the technical emissions?
All synthetic fuels, I think.
There are literally tons of documents.
I know.
And ERDA itself has published, I suspect, wagon loads of material.
And how to ever get that indexed into a...
into something and somebody could quickly find what he wanted.
I have no idea how you do that.
Well, I think they're considering only documents coming out of Germany, not things done since Germany.
That would... Of course, there's a lot of
a lot of published literature out of Germany.
Actually, since the war, the Germans have done almost nothing on collagenation or the fission process or synthetic fuels generally, because they have been using oil that they imported mostly.
So in effect, it seems to me that

If you could confine your indexing to the technical oil mission documents, well, this might be a possible approach to it, but to consider a broader area would mean an awful lot of literature had to be considered.
from IRDA and from the Bureau of Mines and from the Office of Coal Research and from the universities and everybody else.
Because there's been work going on all over the United States in particular and in a number of other countries as well.
OK. Well, from the documents brought back to Germany, then.
From Germany.
From Germany.
The war documents, really, for lack of a better word, the documents that we
selected in Germany and shipped back to this country and to England, if those were going to be indexed and cataloged, should they begin the technical oil mission?
Or should they begin exploring other archives?
Of course, there was a lot of work in Germany.
done, well, practically all the work was done for the technical oil mission.

So I would, I guess you really ought to consider all the work that was done in the 1920 to 1940 period, which was published in Germany, and then add to that all the work that was brought back for the technical oil mission.
And let me think just a minute.
It's really a field that I don't consider myself very well qualified in this business index and documents.
But the Bureau of Mining, you know, has published
Indices of patents and...
Yeah, this is the... You got that?
Yeah, this is the index of the microfilm reels of technical oil emissions.
It's not synthetic fuel, but it's part of the synthetic fuel.
Well, I think what's being considered is to go through the German documents and abstract the information and place it on a computer.
Should they begin with technical oil emission documents, or should they begin with other documents?
Now, there's an index like that, I think it's a little bit bigger, on collagenation patents, too.
I'm sure I got it someplace here in the book, in case I can't...
I think there's some 3,000 patents in there.
Just on?
Cohonogenation.
Cohonogenation.
Up to 1950, I believe.
I don't know when that thing was published.
In three parts.
I don't believe I've got the other two parts.
I'm very sorry.
But...
I have read this book.
It's a series of abstracts.
It's just a little piece here.
I think I've read every patent in there.
And you see here I've made whole notes on the whole thing, trying to anchor into my mind what the previous technology was.
I don't remember exactly how this is divided up, but I'm sure there's some classification in here, patents.
I guess it's just, maybe it's chronologically, I don't know, or patent number or something like that.
I don't know how to do that, John, that you're talking about.
We've, the Bureau of Mine says, as you see it, made attempts at certain sections of it.
But I don't think, I don't know as if, I don't know whether you can improve on what's already been done or whether you can't.
I'm sure you can put all that in a computer so maybe you can index it in some way so you can call up what you want with less trouble and this, but I really don't know how to do that.
Yeah, I think they're talking about making a box by box and item by item search of all the German documents brought over and abstracting those.
Well, good luck to you.
Well, assuming that's what they're going to do, should they begin with the TOM documents?
Should they begin out random?
I'm talking really just in terms of personal opinion.
I really realize that you don't have any.
Well, the TOM documents only cover a small segment of the coal, hydrogenation, and fission droppers technology.
That's the trouble.
It does, huh?
Yeah.
And the others are found outside of Germany?
Some of them may be found in Germany and many of them outside of Germany.
I see.
They're all over the world, the United States, England, everywhere.
You bet.
Okay.
Now, have some of the documents been in effect lost or destroyed since they've been stored here, as far as you know?
In other words, are there sizable blocks or documents missing anyplace?
Well, to my knowledge, I don't really know, but I don't know where they were stored in the first place.
I only have the vaguest idea of where they were stored.
And this is a hearsay story that you can maybe check out on, but we did...
a lot of work in Louisiana, Missouri, as you know, and recorded it in the annual reports.
But the annual reports are not very detailed reports.
And a lot of the detailed data that we got from Louisiana, Missouri, was supposedly stored at Pittsburgh.
Well, later on, it was moved from Pittsburgh to Morgantown, West Virginia.
And then IRDA authorized a restudy of that Louisiana, Missouri data.
And they authorized Floor to restudy that data plus some other data from the Office of Coal Research and various other places.
And the Floor people told me that they went down to Morgantown and the documents from Louisiana, Missouri had all been destroyed shortly before they got there as it happened.
So that's the only thing I know of officially that's been lost and destroyed.
But I don't know what happened to all the files that the Department of Commerce had either, except I guess you said they were microfilmed.
Yeah, they're supposed to have been microfilmed.
According to these charts I went through, they're supposed to have been microfilmed and sent out.
And allegedly, Private Enterprise could check this index
and call for something they wanted.
I presume that's what the index was for.
Well, it seems to me I have some vague recollection that they did try to preserve this on microfilm so people could get it if they wanted it at some future date.
But whether it was actually done or not, I don't know.
And presumably that you could read through the indexes.
And if something interested you, they're supposed to be able to call those out for you to go through some kind of report.
I don't know.
Technical oil mission, though, now, it's really much more concerned with other things than petroleum, is it not?
Well, the technical oil mission, if you consider TOM directly, we were really confined all our efforts to synthetic fuel.
I got a damn Greek I'm supposed to talk to about a report, I think.

Well, you know, frankly, the problem I have is I don't know what documents have been looked at and what documents haven't been looked at and where they're stored and what they are and whether they're duplicate or not duplicate documents.
And so your problem is unless you know them.
After you leave the bureau... You know, I sort of wonder... Did you talk to Ernie to see if they've made any surveys of the previous legislature?
No.
Well, they've hired an awful lot of people to do an awful lot of studying.
And I wonder if they might not be a good place to start.
We did a lot of work at the Bureau of Mines on surveying the earth literature, as you see here.
But that work was pretty well wound up in the early 50s, and it ought to be carried forward beyond the time the Bureau of Mines has carried it forward.
Now, it's possible the Office of Coal Research has done some.
You know, I think another group you ought to talk to is Ephraim.
I don't know how much studying, I don't know how much reviewing they've done of literature out there.
But I think Erda's really a better group to start with.
You leave the Bureau of Mines in 1952.
I inferred from your interview you left it because you felt like they would do nothing else with synthetic fuels.
Is that correct?
Yeah, I wouldn't say that they would do nothing with synthetic fuels, but I felt that the interest in synthetic fuels had gone downhill at a very large rate because of oil in the Middle East.
uh... tend to lose track of synthetic fuels?
I don't... that's not... that's not... Well... From 53 to 62, you don't seem to be very active in synthetic fuels.
Is that fair?
Except at that work I did at Spencer Chemical Company in El Paso, a natural gas company.
Okay.
And then from 60, uh...
I took out those patents in the early 60s.
And from 60 to 68, I did very little in synthetic fuels because I was working then on, uh...
Actually, I was very much more busy with my consulting work, and I was working on building ammonia plants and things of that nature.
So there was a period of about seven years in there, which I did relatively little in synthetic oil.
And then when the Arab, well, before the Arab scare came up, the Academy of Engineers started to review, again, gasification processes and so forth.
And I started to work with them, and that aroused my interest again.
And that's how you come back to it.
Yeah.
That started about 1967, 68.
And I'll tell you another thing that brought me back to it was the Union Pacific asked me to take a look at the possibility of coal mining on the Union Pacific Railroad.
And this was about the time we got into our environmental problems with the power plants and so on and so forth.
And that work for the Union Pacific brought me back into synthetic fuels.
And I take it that presently at least you're not optimistic about synthetic fuels solving the nation's oil crises.
I wouldn't say that I'm optimistic.
I said you're not optimistic.
I'm not optimistic.
I believe that if we can get
a substantial improvement in existing processes by hydrogenating coal directly with hydrogen gas that we got a chance of helping ourselves greatly on our oil supply century.
Does that sum it up for you?
Mm-hmm.
Sure does.
